On 19 October 1978 the PDPA government introduced a new flag, a red flag with a yellow seal, and it was similar to the flags of the [[Soviet Central Asia]]n republics.{{sfn|Edwards|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=biOdjgEO-IcC&amp;pg=PA30 30]}} The new flag stirred popular resentment, many Afghans saw it as proof of the PDPA government's secular nature.{{sfn|Tomsen|2011|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=zz9_Ve29eL0C&amp;pg=PA133 133]}} It was shown to the public for the first time in an official rally in Kabul.{{sfn|Runion|2007|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=aZk9XzqCFGUC&amp;pg=PA106 106]}} The red flag introduced under Taraki was replaced in 1980, shortly after the Soviet intervention, to the more traditional colours black, red and green. The PDPA flag, which was red with a yellow seal, was retained to emphasise the difference between the party and state to the Afghan people.{{sfn|Male|1982|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-cYOAAAAQAAJ&amp;pg=PA212 212]}} The red star, the book and communist symbols in general, were removed from the flag in 1987 under Najibullah.{{sfn|Yassari|2005|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=CMGfLzYWeW4C&amp;pg=PA15 15]}}
{{multiple image
| align             = left
| direction         = horizontal
| header            = The emblems of Afghanistan during PDPA rule
| header_align      = center
| header_background =
| footer            =
| footer_align      = center
| footer_background =
| width             =
| image1            = Emblem of Afghanistan (1978-1980).svg
