| width2            = 130
| caption2          = 1980–1987
| image3            = Emblem of Afghanistan (1987-1992).svg
| width3            = 141
| caption3          = 1987–1992
}}
The new emblem, which replaced Daoud's eagle emblem, was introduced together with the flag in 1978.{{sfn|Misdaq|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=Zvm9dxavH-IC&amp;pg=PA119 119]}} When Karmal introduced a new emblem in 1980, he said &quot;it is from the pulpit that thousands of the faithful are led to the right path.&quot;{{sfn|Edwards|2002|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=biOdjgEO-IcC&amp;pg=PA91 91]}} The book depicted in the emblem (and the flag) was generally considered to be ''[[Das Kapital]]'', a work by [[Karl Marx]], and not the ''[[Quran]]'', the central Islamic text.{{sfn|Kamali|1985|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=ksC-BL2WivUC&amp;pg=PA33 33]}} The last emblem was introduced in 1987 by the Najibullah government. This emblem was, in contrast to the previous ones, influenced by [[Islam]].{{sfn|Achcar|2004|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=8FNIchn0jJMC&amp;pg=PA103 103]}} The Red Star and ''Das Kapital'' were removed from the emblem (and the flag).{{sfn|Yassari|2005|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=CMGfLzYWeW4C&amp;pg=PA15 15]}} The emblem depicted the [[mihrab]], the [[minbar]] and the [[shahada]], an Islamic creed.{{sfn|Ende|2010|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=-dM4hPlxMw8C&amp;pg=PA268 268]}}
{{clear}}

==Economy==
